Feature extraction - Look at unstructured data, create new vars (e.g., time of day in terms of hours, quoted vs.non, picture vs.no, sentiment for each word) - Use new features to train model as to whether tweet is from android/iphone - DV - iPhone/android - IV = all those created variables/features

How to analyze dataset? Examine predictions - iPhone/android use as function of non-word features - Unnest a couple words at a time, not just singular words [but this might backfire: a) harder to clean jump, b) not all text will work]

Automate algorithm by trying to make predictions without going one by one through the data/being as reliant on the data

Additional methods of classification?

1) Naive bayes classifier; new info changes our estimations of probability

Green and red dice (5, and 4, respectively; 1/6 chances for each individaully)

without knowing color x2 5s, x2 4s = 1/18

knowing color x2 5s, x2 4s = 1/36, updates information

given that C happens, As probability is? P(A|C) P(4|5) = 1/6 (throws are independent, nothing affects 4)

EX. home, work, bar P(bar) = 1/3 - Not accurate; needs updating.. what if its 5am? - Calculate P(bar|5am); P(bar|5am|saturday); additional features

P(bar | time, weekend, weather, stress) Traditional Bayes: creates long chain, connects everything - P(stress) x P(weather | stress) x P(weekend | weather, stress) x etc.

Naive Bayes: treats every additional factor independently - P(Bar) = P(bar|weather) x P(bar|weekend) x P(bar|stress) - Easier to calculate conditional probabilities, important since we often dont have complete info

Good for text mining since it can use multiple words and see how one word might depend on prev word - All that amtters for new word to appear is the word prior to it

2) Support Vector Machines (svm)

Similar to trees - use trees to separate data points, but they get complex very quickly - limited to horizontal/vertical cuts - More accurate, less flexible

svm can grow tree with single branch in different ways - one line = support vector (linear; can also be non-linear cuts) - complex trees not needed if there is way to rotate coordinates & make tree using diff coordinates - there will always be some error stil - More flexible

EX. for spiral data, support vector would not be as effective - When edge between clusters are extremely non-linear - base approach using accuracy metrics (if 2D data, svm generally better)
